On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphal return to the political scene at the national level.
According to the preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remained, with 29.8 per cent of the votes, the country's first political force, however, compared with the 2006 elections, lost 5.5 per cent of the votes.
The ÖVP, with 25.6 per cent losing almost nine per cent of the votes, ended even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the people's party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the popular party had a considerable advance on the SPÖ.
However, voters obviously punished them for letting the government collapse.
