Such a change would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the large SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the free (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the votes - the socialists at the same time expressed the fear of a repeat of 1999, when the popular party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ separated from it) on a common government, which even raised sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he was ready to work with any party and that he planned to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently put on this evolution.
The last party to have access to parliament being the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell, among the Austrian political parties, from the third in fifth position.
Obviously, no other party crosses the limit of four percent and does not access parliament.
