The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Centre developed this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C represents the development of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow brand vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee created its own personal space of an oval shape that much resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important is the eyes composed of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles that lie within a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor immediately to avoid the obstacle.
"When it detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcing its wheels of 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, "explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Movement Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotational function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
" Every second this device must only process information and act according to this data.
It doesn't need to keep the information or intuitive logics of pre-manufacturing, that's why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise us, but we don't talk about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This represents the first step towards developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into serial cars in about ten years after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
