Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, he was the third to put a draft new Constitution to the vote.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results of 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the polls and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a large "yes" victory, between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on Sunday night to Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place calmly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), covered a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" advocated by the President.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State on the economy, by reserving to it the "planning of development" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Brought by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives enhanced powers to the Head of State, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive terms of four years and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it would use this power and challenge a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in that country 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back this Monday healthy and safe in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at the military base of al-Maza, hosted at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 Special Forces personnel, on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunshots took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official who requested the anonymity.
He indicated that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "light" unit had been sent to Sudan in total, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result through the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The previous day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on a patrol where the kidnappers were on board, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unit Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
