Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Holland bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. The three countries support, to a sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, also by calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition manager.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has grown for more than a year is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy nearly half (up to 49%) of the bank's capital in each country.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its stakes, among which, first and foremost, the activities, mainly insurance, it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares started a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let it go bankrupt.
Just on Friday, the company's shares fell by 12 percent to reach its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the capital of the group revolves around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's leaders, is unrealistic.
The company's management is facing the uncertainty of the other Atlantic, in relation to the adoption of the US $700 billion rescue plan, to be the cause of the fall of the Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received any proposals on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also purchased leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of information regarding prescriptions of medicinal products, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise this is to entrust his chicken to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions for drugs, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies rely on the insurance premium and the insured capital in the event of injury, the health status of the client, and if they feel the risk is too high, they do not even guarantee it.
In the past, they sent candidates to a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after they became aware of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is easily provided to pharmacies, the data on the purchase of medication from the person in the last eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what his state of health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. At the same time, some determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much to be done to the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still arise.
Among the disadvantages of this program are the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat puffs, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers to be an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data, and they must apply for permission from the patient before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are constrained by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their past failings.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory analysis results, linking them with data on drug use, and in this way they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and the control of use is becoming more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the expansion of the control circle of authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus and in the end, chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are increasing their trade by two.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit next to the other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a France-India Summit, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be the main issue.
The European Union recognizes that India is a major emerging democratic power to which a broader right of speech should be given in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not focus too much on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Head of Diplomacy Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would multiply trade by two, which means a rise of about 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods has risen from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be a too ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, and air trade will also be able to grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only in ninth place among EU partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and there was an urgent need to hold a United Nations conference on this issue.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic substances by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as on the need for a global market at next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now going to the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to information from the press agency, the agreement would cover 15 years.
