Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire missing a year ago.
The wreck of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire disappeared on 3 September 2007 while flying in the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at 3000 metres above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, overcame the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have the confirmation that it is the one on which Steve Fosset was traveling the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore specified that no human remains were found on or around the aircraft.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreck was spotted, a team of investigators sent to the scene, identified the aircraft: it was Bellanca 8kcab, disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal effects were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes residence.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's research was interrupted one month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had gained a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
At the sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete the world round on an aerostatic balloon in 2002, two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world without a stopover.
Among all these records, also that of stealing at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a copilot.
